<br><b><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#4681BD" weight="bold">.:How (not) to snowboard.:.</font></b><br>
<small><font size="1" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" color="#0F7B66">Saturday, January 11 2003</font></small><br><br>

<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><font color="#FFFFFF">When snowboarding:</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Make sure to stay either on the toe or heel edge of the board at all times. This prevents you from hitting a bump and doing a bad martial arts fall impression.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Always keep your weight on the lead foot/leg, so as to free your rear leg for ruddering as well as keeping a forward center of balance.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
What not to do:</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Do not catch the wrong edge of the snowboard in a pile of snow, subsequently leading to a catapult like motion forcing your face to meet ice/snow and then slide on said face for 10 feet. Results in red face with lots of lost skin.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
Do not make a sharp turn and hit a mound of ice, especially in areas where the trail is particularly narrow. Could end in snowboarded falling off teh trail into the thick underbrush nearby and being punctured by branches in the back of the knee. Quite painful.</P><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>
</p></font></font>
